Today's pick: **SyntheMol-RL** — Jon Stokes' lab (the Halicin people) just published in *Molecular Systems Biology* (April 23). It's a reinforcement-learning generative framework that searches a 46-billion-compound space built from 150K synthesizable building blocks, jointly optimizing antibacterial activity, water solubility, and novelty. They synthesized 79 of its top picks → 13 active in vitro → **synthecin** cleared a drug-resistant MRSA wound infection in a mouse model as a topical cream. The architectural move that matters: replacing Monte Carlo tree search with a learned value function over building-block features, which actually generalizes and unlocks multi-parameter optimization. Synthesizability baked into the chemical space (not filtered post-hoc) is the right design decision, and this architecture transfers far beyond antibiotics. [Paper](https://link.springer.com/article/10.1038/s44320-026-00206-9)

