Kuan-lin Huang's group at Mount Sinai, with the new Accelerated Discovery with Agents (ADA) Consortium, ran an agent on 31 published oncology target claims with retraction status as a quasi-orthogonal ground-truth label. Non-retracted claims validated at 64.3% (9/14); retracted at 11.8% (2/17) — a 17-fold differential. Replicated set spans WRN/MSS, PRMT5/MTAP-deleted, plus newer hits (PTGES3, HASPIN, SLC5A3, PKMYT1, FAM126B, PAPSS1). The retraction-as-orthogonal-label framing is the move — it's the kind of external audit pharma agentic AI deployments need before anyone trusts their target prioritization output. The 11% false-positive rate on retracted means agent-driven validation can't be a sole gate but works as one signal in a portfolio.

